se of evidence from ancient texts and contemporary interviews, male-authored documents and women's possession experiences, myth, ritual, and folklore. Arguing that Mahadevi has multiple, context-dependent identities that are constructed through human interpretive activity, this book highlights the great diversity of ways that those who worship Mahadevi conceive of and portray her.Contributors include C. Mackenzie Brown, Sarah Caldwell, Thomas Coburn, Elaine Craddock, Kathleen M. Erndl, Jeffrey J. Kripal, Usha Menon, Tracy Pintchman, Andhra Pradesh, and Mark Edwin Rohe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHindu goddesses. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, C. Mackenzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoburn, Thomas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraddock, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErndl, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEss, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKripal, Jeffrey J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenon, Usha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadma, Sree, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPintchman, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPintchman, Tracy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRohe, Mark Edwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org